    ROOT CAUSE                                                                  
    In the function convert_fileName() a fixed‑size stack buffer char           
    newname[MAX] (where MAX is defined as 2048) is filled by a manual for‑loop  
    that copies each character of the argument original until the terminating   
    '\0' is seen. The loop iterates blindly on the length of original without   
    ever verifying that the index i stays below MAX. When a filename longer     
    than 2047 characters is supplied, the copy writes past the end of newname,  
    overwriting adjacent stack slots such as the saved frame pointer and        
    return address. The corrupted return address no longer points to valid      
    code, so when the function returns control is transferred to an unmapped    
    address, causing the process to receive a segmentation fault (the “crash”   
    observed). This is exactly what the sanitizer / crash report describes: a   
    stack buffer overflow caused by missing bounds checking on the input        
    length.                                                                     
                                                                                
    LOCAL FIX                                                                   
    The simplest change that stops the immediate crash is to enforce a hard     
    limit on the number of characters copied and to guarantee                   
    null‑termination:                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
      // original code (simplified)                                             
     - for (size_t i = 0; original[i] != '\0'; ++i) {                           
     -     newname[i] = original[i];                                            
     - }                                                                        
     - newname[i] = '\0';                                                       
                                                                                
     + // bounded copy – never write more than MAX‑1 characters                 
     + size_t max_copy = strlen(original);                                      
     + if (max_copy >= MAX) {                                                   
     +     // Option 1: truncate (most benign for a CLI tool)                   
     +     max_copy = MAX - 1;                                                  
     + }                                                                        
     + // strncpy does not guarantee null‑termination if source length ==       
     max_copy                                                                   
     + memcpy(newname, original, max_copy);                                     
     + newname[max_copy] = '\0';                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or even more idiomatic:                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
         strncpy(newname, original, MAX - 1);                                   
         newname[MAX - 1] = '\0';          // ensure terminator                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Both modifications guarantee that no more than MAX‑1 bytes are written to   
    newname, preventing overflow of the stack and protecting the return         
    address.                                                                    
                                                                                
    GLOBAL FIX                                                                  
    The deeper design flaw is the reliance on a fixed‑size stack buffer for an  
    arbitrarily sized filename. A robust design would eliminate that            
    stack‑allocated buffer altogether, for example by:                          
                                                                                
     1 Using a length‑safe abstraction – accept or return a std::string (or a   
       bounded view type) instead of a raw C‑style buffer.                      
                                                                                
        std::string convert_fileName(const std::string& original) {             
            // Reserve at most MAX‑1 characters, or fail / truncate as policy   
            size_t max_len = std::min(original.size(), MAX - 1);                
            return original.substr(0, max_len);                                 
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
     2 Explicit input validation at the entry point – before calling            
       convert_fileName() verify that the supplied filename length conforms to  
       policy (e.g., reject > MAX‑1 characters and return an error code). This  
       moves the responsibility of size limiting out of the utility function    
       into the layer that parses command‑line arguments.                       
     3 Adopting safer string utilities – replace manual loops with functions    
       that perform bounds checking (strlcpy, snprintf, or C++20                
       std::ranges::copy_n). These functions either truncate automatically or   
       return an error when the source does not fit.                            
     4 Compile‑time enforcement – add a static_assert(MAX > 0, "MAX must be     
       positive") and possibly constexpr size_t MaxFilename = 2048; to          
       centralize the limit, making it obvious to future maintainers that any   
       change must be reviewed.                                                 
                                                                                
    By removing the raw stack buffer and enforcing a clear invariant on         
    filename length, the program can no longer overflow its own stack,          
    eliminating the class of bugs that lead to crashes when users supply        
    unusually long filenames. This global redesign also improves code clarity,  
    testability, and future maintainability.                                    
